1
00:00:00.300 --> 00:00:07.020
In this lecture, let's take a moment to explore the various resources at our disposal for WordPress

2
00:00:07.020 --> 00:00:07.950
development.

3
00:00:07.980 --> 00:00:12.930
Throughout this course, I have been throwing links at you for various functions.

4
00:00:12.930 --> 00:00:19.200
In my opinion, WordPress is very well documented, however it is very large.

5
00:00:19.200 --> 00:00:24.750
Being able to navigate the documentation will help you with your journey as a developer.

6
00:00:24.750 --> 00:00:30.420
You can follow along with me by checking out the links in the resource section of this lecture.

7
00:00:30.450 --> 00:00:34.710
First things first we should make a distinction between the two sites.

8
00:00:34.710 --> 00:00:41.340
If we were to search for WordPress, two results would appear which are WordPress.com and WordPress

9
00:00:41.340 --> 00:00:42.300
dot org.

10
00:00:42.300 --> 00:00:47.190
They have similar domain names, but there's one huge distinction between them.

11
00:00:47.190 --> 00:00:51.420
The dot com domain is a hosting platform for WordPress.

12
00:00:51.520 --> 00:00:57.660
After we're finished developing a WordPress site, the next step is to upload our code to a hosting

13
00:00:57.660 --> 00:00:58.440
provider.

14
00:00:58.440 --> 00:01:03.840
There are dozens of providers available that exclusively deal with WordPress sites.

15
00:01:03.840 --> 00:01:09.120
The WordPress hosting platform is just one of the many hosts available.

16
00:01:09.120 --> 00:01:13.290
It's completely optional to upload your code to this platform.

17
00:01:13.290 --> 00:01:15.210
Let's keep moving forward.

18
00:01:15.210 --> 00:01:18.330
The dot org domain does not host sites.

19
00:01:18.330 --> 00:01:22.350
Instead it'll host the original source code of WordPress.

20
00:01:22.350 --> 00:01:28.530
It's the same code you'll find in the app slash public directory of our local installation.

21
00:01:28.770 --> 00:01:31.890
WordPress is 100% open source.

22
00:01:31.890 --> 00:01:35.580
There are no fees associated with downloading WordPress.

23
00:01:35.580 --> 00:01:39.810
We can download WordPress, read the code and modify it.

24
00:01:39.810 --> 00:01:46.380
If you're interested in downloading the source code of WordPress, you can do so at the dot org domain.

25
00:01:46.650 --> 00:01:51.300
Throughout this course, we're going to be spending most of our time on this site.

26
00:01:51.300 --> 00:01:53.910
Let's keep exploring under support.

27
00:01:53.910 --> 00:01:55.650
Click Documentation.

28
00:01:57.890 --> 00:02:02.840
This part of the site will provide documentation on WordPress features.

29
00:02:02.870 --> 00:02:09.380
This documentation will go over the basics of WordPress such as installation and configuration.

30
00:02:09.410 --> 00:02:16.520
It seemed that individuals who don't know how to code the technical details of WordPress are not documented

31
00:02:16.520 --> 00:02:18.230
on this part of the site.

32
00:02:18.440 --> 00:02:21.370
WordPress documents the technical details.

33
00:02:21.380 --> 00:02:25.370
Elsewhere, scroll to the bottom of the page on the footer.

34
00:02:25.400 --> 00:02:27.120
There's a link for developers.

35
00:02:27.140 --> 00:02:28.520
Let's click on it.

36
00:02:30.690 --> 00:02:33.800
The developer site is aimed at programmers.

37
00:02:33.810 --> 00:02:37.650
It's going to be your most valuable resource as a developer.

38
00:02:37.650 --> 00:02:42.030
Before digging deeper, there's another resource worth mentioning.

39
00:02:42.030 --> 00:02:43.740
It's called Codex.

40
00:02:43.740 --> 00:02:47.940
The Codex was the original place for a WordPress documentation.

41
00:02:47.940 --> 00:02:54.780
Back in the early days, WordPress used the codex resource for everything from code examples to simple

42
00:02:54.780 --> 00:02:57.060
explanations about the user system.

43
00:02:57.060 --> 00:03:02.670
However, as WordPress grew, the documentation became bloated with information.

44
00:03:02.670 --> 00:03:07.560
It was difficult to navigate for technical and non technical users.

45
00:03:07.560 --> 00:03:13.080
As a result, they separated the developer and user friendly documentation.

46
00:03:13.230 --> 00:03:16.200
The codex resource is no longer supported.

47
00:03:16.200 --> 00:03:20.550
In a few years it'll be completely removed from time to time.

48
00:03:20.550 --> 00:03:23.640
The Codex resource contains code examples.

49
00:03:23.640 --> 00:03:30.330
The WordPress team has not completed the transition from the Codex resource to the developer resource.

50
00:03:30.330 --> 00:03:34.290
It's a work in progress in almost all instances.

51
00:03:34.290 --> 00:03:39.060
You'll want to refer to the documentation on the developer resource.

52
00:03:39.060 --> 00:03:42.480
The codex resource will eventually be retired.

53
00:03:42.510 --> 00:03:47.790
The available resource is kept up to date with the latest changes in WordPress.

54
00:03:47.790 --> 00:03:51.090
Let's learn how to take advantage of this resource.

55
00:03:51.090 --> 00:03:57.060
The main page of the developer resource will contain links to different topics of WordPress.

56
00:03:57.060 --> 00:04:03.030
For example, if we want to learn about themes, we can click on the Themes section.

57
00:04:03.030 --> 00:04:06.660
We'll be exploring these topics throughout this course.

58
00:04:06.690 --> 00:04:12.120
Most sections will take you to a handbook to learn the basics of each feature.

59
00:04:12.120 --> 00:04:16.230
The most important section is the code reference section.

60
00:04:16.230 --> 00:04:17.700
Let's check it out.

61
